reasonably easy to do.

>The only solution to the above problem is to set time acceleration to
>some higher value.  If I sit back and enjoy the full show at lower
>speed, it will most certainly kill me.

Er, you've just pegged the solution to your problems... :)

The autopilot _cheats_, basically. If you're (say) landed at San Francisco
and you want to go to Moscow, on the other side of the planet, and activate
the autopilot, it will see that Moscow is ^7000 miles below you and eagerly
smash you into the ground. But if you peg the fastest accelerated time
value, you'll be in Moscow safe and sound in the blink of an eye.

This works for space stations _and_ ground bases. Peg the top accelerated
time setting while autopilot is on, and you'll be perfectly safe. Leave it
on a lower setting to watch how the autopilot does it, and you'll discover
that the autopilot _doesn't_ do it. This ought to get some attention
in the next version, no question, but in the meantime just use accelerated
time and you'll be fine. (While we're at it, how about airplane-style
autopilot on planets, so you can make cross-country flights? :) And
move New York back on land, too... :-o)

