In article <srn.752884160@orthanc> srn@cs.su.oz.au (Stephen Robert Norris) writes:
> sgberg@charon.bloomington.in.us (Stefan G. Berg) writes:
> 
> >The nice thing about Elite I is that no matter what, you can't equip
> >your ship so well that you can basically ignore enemy ships. Battle in
> >Elite I was pretty easy once you had a well equipped ship, but at
> >least it kept you occupied for a few seconds. In Frontier it doesn't
> >even do that.
> 
> 	You must have been a rotton Elite player, with 4 military lasers &
> ECM and all the rest, combat became a matter of holding down the fire button
> and wobbling until the ships exploded.

Fortunately that is not possible in Elite I, since enemy ships do not
come as a single block. You have them arranged in a star configuration
like this:

   *     *
      *
   *     *

In the initial phase your three rear and side lasers are useless, so
you have to aim quickly and destroy as many as possible before they
start separating. If none of them are tough ships you can generally
do that, but only one Thargoid and this approach won't work anymore. By
the time the Thargoid is destroyed, the laser as approach maximum heat
and the others have started to separate. So you do end up having to
actually chase them, but as I already mentioned, that is practically
always a very simple process and damage is minimal if at all.

Unless you had a different version of Elite I must say that you must
have either a rotten memory or didn't really mean what you said. It is
not possible timewise to destroy them all in this initial phase if
there is a Thargoid or a Wolf under them, no matter how good you are
and even with Military laser. And once they have left their initial
configuration, you cannot simply "wobble". You must actually move more
than a few degrees and in tough combats you might even need to chase a
few.

I don't think I am too rotten at Elite I. A standard combat starts out
with a quick location of the enemy configuration and from then on my
finger doesn't leave the fire button anymore. It takes me a fraction
of a second to relocate the laser beam on the next ship once a ship
explodes. So I reach maximum efficiency. Still, there are combinations
of enemy ships where my laser overheats and I start getting into enemy
fire. At that point you _must_ change your current flight of path
otherwise you'll be dead meat quickly.

Though I agree, that Elite I combats did not increase in difficulty as
quickly as your increase in aiming efficiency.  But at least a combat
in Elite I was a combat.  In Frontier a combat with the right ship is
not even a combat anymore. Most of the time enemy ships just run into
me and I don't even get a good aim at them. Ship damage is minimal
(20% on shields maybe).

I guess Frontier expects you to adjust the difficulty level on your
own. That means, if you want to get into tough fights, then you should
degrade your ship protection and weapon capabilities until you think
it is difficult enough. I personally don't like it this way, it takes
out some of the challenge.

Stefan

