From Michel Brown...

....demo still sputters and spits..doesn't run properly....

I would think that something in your machine environment is stopping the
demo working. I have had no trouble with crashes. Certainly does not need
a stack size greater than 65K.

As for the game, if you are a space enthusiast, get it. Regardless of the game
component, the space simulation is an educational feast. Accurate rendering
of planet sizes, distances, orbits, declinations, gravitational attraction
(have fun putting your space-ship in geo-synchronous orbit. Take a trip to
Pluto, yes you can find it on the system map with careful zooming. An odd bug
in V1.00 stops you landing on Pluto, but you can land on Charon and watch
Pluto <apparently> revolving around Charon every 7 days). 

The best tool yet for teaching kids about the solar system (and lots of other
systems). They can get really involved. Distant Suns is first-class in an
abstract way and, of course, very accurate, but there's nothing like piloting
your own space-ship across the galaxy. Frontier gives kids that 'experience'.

I congratulate David Braben on a marvellous achievement. The 'avid games
players' have fired lots of criticism about the depth of game-play etc. Some
is definitely justified, some distinctly over the top. However, these people
are narrowly focussed on the 'gaming experience' (after all, they paid
good money for it) 
and have chosen to miss a  wonderful educational dimension. Frontier is more
an 'experience' than a 'game'. 

On the game-play and 'silly' bugs, I am sure that David will capture the
good suggestions and offer the user-community some update mechanism. He is
obviously very interested in something to which he has given 5 years of
dedicated work and is justifiable proud of it.


 
John Lewis

