In article <2brdf0$cb5@davinci.uni-paderborn.de> laire@davinci.uni-paderborn.de (Ralph Schmidt) writes:

>Sorry but that's wrong.
>I was in the same situation and refueling didn't help at all.
>I solved the problem by driving through one of the base walls and
>start outside:-B

I've since encountered the non-refueling version of this problem.  Quite right
it >IS< a bug.  Solution; point yourself at one of the base walls (I go towards
the big sign) and hit enter to build up a little motion.  Then, before you hit
the wall hit max time compression.  This gets you outside free and clear
without damaging the undercarriage (going from a standing start will damage
your landing gear).  Sometimes it doesn't work... this always seems to be tied
to the wall you choose... I'd guess you are 'jumping out' into the planet
itself in that case... just try the other walls until you find a good one.

>I always use time compression...otherwise it would take too long.
>It's probably more realistic but it's not good for the gameplay.

Well, slightly under max compression for the short space required to reach the
enemy without 'jumping' them shouldn't be a problem.  However, there IS another
way to get multiple enemies.  Do a photo mission and stick around for a bit.
The target will launch MANY MANY MANY different ships to come after you.  Very
fun in the dogfighting department.

>>Truth:  I had an imperial courier with 20 shield generators taken out by a
>>single foe in about one second.  I never even saw him as more than a blip on
>>the scanner.  One of the giant ships like a panther could probably have taken
>>that... but what about two or three of them?  Besides which... the panther is
>>hard to destroy because of it's size, but it's just not workable for time
>>constraints on missions.

>I use a panther and there's no ship(s) yet that could cause some serious
>damage. I also don't need an autopilot in a battle.

I've run into opponents that could take out a panther.  The above mentioned
'cloud' of enemies around a protracted photo mission would chew a bulky panther
to pieces in no time.  NOT that it's likely to happen since there is almost NO
way a plodding panther could ever COMPLETE a photo mission on time.  The
panther is GREAT one on one if you don't care about getting somewhere fast.
However, for the advanced missions it's basically worhtless.  Indeed, I've had
to trade in my Imperial Courier because IT was too slow.  Now I'm flying a
Tiger Trader... which I believe is the closest to the 'ideal ship' in the game.
Fuel scoops, 12.5 ly (with class 5), 12.x acceleration, room for good weapons,
room for fuel for 2 jumps.  It's not QUITE what I'd want (15 ly and accel with
about 25 more space for cargo and gadgets would be true perfection) but it's
good enough for almost any mission.  The panther is hopeless for anything but
the simple stuff.

