In article <CGnCKz.71I@cs.bham.ac.uk> nmc@cs.bham.ac.uk writes:
>Could someone post again how the wormhole bug works? I hadn't bought the game last time it came up...

Alright, I haven't checked it too thoroughly (having more interesting things
to examine in the game), but I believe it works as follows;

Wherever your ship is located in three dimensional space is used to determine
the number of tons of fuel required to jump to a nearby system.  Additionally
(likely due to overflow problems) a circle which is the locus of all points
660 lightyears from your current location is treated AS your current location.
A similar circle occurs at 1320 lightyears... and I suspect the next is at
either 1980 or 2640 (multiples of 660 or doubling every time).  Note that this
is true for a Tiger Trader with class 5 warp... I >THINK< the wormhole effect
is constant regardless of ship and drive type, but I might be mistaken...
again, I haven't looked into it for more than about two minutes real time.

The area you can jump to can thus be described as follows where l=your drive's
jump range;

within l lightyears of current x,y,z coordinates   AND
within l lightyears of any point 660 lightyears from current x,y,z coordinates
within l lightyears of any point 1320 lightyears from x,y,z coordinates
etc.....

The 660 figure also might be slightly off... could be 663 or 657... whatever,
it's somewhere around there, and it definitely forms a circle around your
present location.

Thus, if you want to take the express route to some specific distant system
you can move about in the inhabited regions until you have set yourself up
660 (or 1320 or whatever) lightyears from the destination and jump directly
there from 'normal' space.
